often outrageous figures who inhabited Oscar Wilde’s much-mythologized authorial persona – in forging him, they effectively wrote as Wilde – in order to argue that literary forgery can be reimagined as a form of performance. But to forge Wilde and generate "beautiful untrue things" in his name is not only an exercise in role-playing – it is also crucially a form of imaginative world-making, resembling what we describe today as fan fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aOscar Wilde.  aVictorian.  aarchives.  aauthorship.  adrama.  afame.  afan fiction.  aforgery.  afraud.  afraudulent authorship.  aimposture.  aliterary legends.  amodernism.  aqueer.  atwentieth-century British literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751626040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487516260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487516260.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles